PLATT'S OILGRAM PRICE REPORT via NewsNet
January 2, 1996   Vol. 74, No

INTERNATIONAL CRUDE: UNEVENTFUL

   The 15-day Brent market was uneventful with two February Brent cargoes
done at $18.53 and a partial done at $18.51. February Brent/Dubai talked at
$1.20-1.25 while February/March Dubai talked at plus 24-30 cts and
March/April Dubai talked at plus 21-25 cts. January 2-5 Brent CFDs were
pegged at February plus 35-40 cts. January 8-12 Brent CFDs were valued
around February plus 15 cts.
   Prompt physical Brent values moved lower versus February when a January
4-6 cargo changed hands early at February plus 30 cts. But two late-day
trades tightened the market. A January 15-17 was done at 5 cts under
January, equivalent to February plus 67 cts. It was later re-sold at
February plus 60 cts. Talk was tighter during the day so the late deal
coincided somewhat with the market. However, next week's CFDs were rumored
done at plus 37 cts. Based on the three trades, the market was valued at
February plus 52 cts.
   In other dated Brent talk, most were waiting for fresh second decade
January offers while seven sets of Brent dates were kept from the chains.
Six of the dates were kept by a UK major said to hold up to 13 physical
Brent cargoes. Little action took place in other North Sea markets with
Oseberg price differentials to dated widening. An end-January cargo of the
grade was heard done at dated plus 37 cts.
   West African markets were fairly quiet with many still absent due to the
holiday season. The general tone for BQ and Forcados price differentials to
dated was said "reasonably strong." Recent trades were seen breaking the
dated plus 50 ct mark. Offers for light Nigerian grades, loading towards
end-January, were said at the mid 50s over dated Friday.
   Mediterranean Urals trade was thin though prices firmed on back of tight
avails with one deal done at dated plus 15 cts, C+F Augusta, for 80,000mt.
Although the port of Novorossiisk re-opened late Thursday, 19 vessels were 
reportedly waiting to load. Sources said Mediterranean refiners were
seeking alternative crude supplies and were replacing their sour crude
requirements with sweet North Sea barrels.

Copyright 1996 The McGraw-Hill Companies



