January 1996

DIRECT CONVERSION OF METHANE TO METHANOL

This (University of Colorado) report covers a program
to demonstrate the effectiveness of a catalytic
membrane reactor (a ceramic membrane combined with a
catalyst) to solely produce methanol by partial
oxidation of methane.  Methanol synthesis and
separation in one step would make methane more valuable
for producing chemicals and fuels.  Both ceramic and
metal membranes are tested, and similar results are
obtained.  A cooling tube is inserted inside the
membrane reactor to create a low-temperature zone that
rapidly quenches the product stream.  This
non-isothermal non-permselective membrane reactor has
proved effective for increasing methanol selectivity
during CH4 oxidation.

(Order this UTILITY REPORTER reviewed report from
InfoTeam Inc., P.O. Box 15640, Plantation, FL
33318-5640; Phone (954)/or(305) 473-9560, Fax
